bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
105 transmitted and integrated through a hierarchical network that transforms decision-making from 106 perception to action. 107 108 109 Results 110 111 Uncertainty modulates the speed of decisions 112 Participants performed the task first in a training session where individual motion thresholds were 113 estimated for both low and high action uncertainty levels (Fig. 3a). Subsequently, participants 114 performed the task with the motion thresholds that standardized performance, while undergoing 115 MEEG scan.
116 Behavioral performance scaled with levels of perceptual and action uncertainties, confirming the 117 desired effect of task manipulations. During training, participants where slower and less accurate 118 when motion coherence was lower (Fig. 3a). Similarly, during the scan session (Fig. 3b and SI 119 Appendix, Fig. S1) responses were slower under high perceptual (low = 0.77s ±0.1; high = 120 0.88s±0.1; F(1,17) = 158.17 p < 0.0001; post-hoc p < 0.0001; ηp2 = 0.902) and action uncertainty 121 (low = 0.80s ± 0.13; high = 0.85s±0.1; F(1,17) = 6.28 p = 0.022; post-hoc p = 0.022; ηp2 =0.269; 122 2-by-2 repeated measures ANOVA; Tukey-Kramer correction).
123 Participants’ choices were largely independent over trials as indicated by Shannon’s equitability 124 index (mean 0.77 ± 0.016 SD, see SI Appendix and Fig. S2 for statistics) calculated for sequential 125 choice pairs13.
126 Uncertainty modulates the rate of evidence accumulation 127 To decompose the behavioral performance into cognitively relevant latent variables, we fitted 128 accumulation-to-threshold models (Linear Ballistic Accumulator23, LBA), to each participant’s 129 reaction time and accuracy data.
130 Uncertainty can slow responses by reducing the speed of information accumulation (accumulation131 rate), increasing response caution (decision boundary), stretching the time required by perceptual 132 and motor processes not directly related to the decision process (non-decision time), or by a 133 combination thereof. To differentiate these competing mechanisms, we fitted all possible
