bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
134 135 Figure 3. Uncertainty modulates reaction times and the speed of decision evidence accumulation. (a) 136 Decision evidence titrated to the participants’ individual motion sensitivity. Reaction times (left panel) and 137 accuracy (right panel) varied with motion strength (grey lines: individual data, black tick lines: mean data). 138 Low and High perceptual uncertainty were estimated at the 75% and 90% accuracy levels, respectively. (b) 139 During the experiment, reaction times were significantly modulated by both perceptual and action uncertainty 140 (aggregated data for uncertainty type, rm-ANOVA on log(RT) ). (c) The task was modelled using a race 141 accumulation model (Linear ballistic accumulator, LBA). Noisy evidence accumulates over time at a rate v 142 up to a decision bound b. The fastest accumulator (thick blue arrow) determines the choice. Non-decision 143 time linked to sensorial and motor processes (t0) sums to the evidence accumulation time to produce reaction144 times. (d) Bayesian model comparison: changes in the sole drift-rate best accounted for the behavioral data. 145 The quality of fit is also seen by the overlap of empirical reaction time distributions for each condition, with 146 data simulated using the winning model. (e) The model predicted faster accumulation of decision evidence 147 when uncertainty is low for both action and perceptual uncertainty (grey lines connects data points from each 148 participant). (f) Model predicted activity was fitted to the power envelope of the MEEG signal in a trial-by149 trial fashion to identify the latencies of accumulators of decision evidence. Non decision time (t0) was 150 decomposed into pre-accumulation (tau1) and post-accumulation (tau2) time reflecting perceptual and motor 151 processes, respectively.
8

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
152 combinations of free parameters in a set of 15 LBAs. We compared the goodness-of-fit of each 153 model using random-effects Bayesian model comparison24,25. The model comparison revealed that 154 changes in the accumulation-rate alone (model number 2; Fig. 3d top panel) accounted 155 parsimoniously for the effects of uncertainty on behavior. The goodness-of-fit of the winning model 156 was further confirmed by posterior predictive checks (Fig. 3d bottom panel), performed by 157 simulating data under the winning model and then comparing these to the observed data.
158 In the winning model (henceforth, the LBA model), high uncertainty is associated with 159 comparatively slow accumulation rates. This relationship between uncertainty and accumulation 160 rate held for both perception (z = 3.723, p = 0.00019; Wilkoxon sign rank test) and action (z = 161 3.723, p = 0.00019; Wilkoxon sign rank test) uncertainty, as well as for each subject (Fig. 3e), in 162 accord with previous studies11,14.
163 Non-decision time (t0), encompassing sensory delays and motor execution, was estimated to be 164 370ms on average (see SI Appendix, table S1), which is within the plausible range of non-decision 165 times for humans26.
166 167 Localization of decision-evidence accumulation 168 The temporal evolution of the combined MEG and EEG spectral power (power envelope) from 169 each region of interest (ROI) of the parcellated cortical surface served as the signal for our analysis 170 in beta (13-30Hz) and gamma (31-90Hz) bands. The time onset of evidence accumulation across 171 ROIs was identified by optimizing the split of the non-decision time before and after the 172 accumulation period using Spearman correlation to the single-trial MEEG power envelope (Fig. 173 3f, see Methods and Materials for details, supplemental Fig. S3 for the statistical map). This 174 allows one to depict in space and time the emergence of decision-evidence accumulation.
175 In support of our hypothesis that both increasing and non-increasing activity can mediate evidence 176 accumulation27,28, we found significant (negative) correlations between the LBA model predictions 177 and the MEEG oscillations in beta and gamma bands17 (Fig. 4). Specifically, for both beta and 178 gamma, neural activity after coherence onset desynchronized in a graded fashion and peaked 179 approximately before response suggesting a form of threshold mechanism (Fig. 4a)29,30.
180 In the beta band, desynchronization was strongly modulated by uncertainty in good agreement with 181 our predictions. As the decision unfolds, the accumulated decision-evidence will ramp quickly with
9

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
182 low perceptual uncertainty, and slowly with high perceptual uncertainty. Accordingly, 183 desynchronization of beta power-envelopes averaged across trials and ROIs was larger (p < 0.0001, 184 cluster corrected random permutations) for low than high perceptual uncertainty18,29.
185 When a response is chosen between multiple options, the race underlying the selection of each 186 alternative is characterized by an overall larger amount of decision-evidence summed across all he 187 racing accumulators by the time of response13,14. Accordingly, desynchronization of beta power188 envelopes averaged across trials and ROIs was larger for high than low action uncertainty (p < 189 0.0001, cluster corrected random permutations). Gamma power-envelopes, showed a similar trend, 190 but the effects were statistically insignificant.
191 Decision-related dynamics expressed by beta desynchronization were distributed across a wide 192 network (Fig3b, mean across significant ROIs: sign-test z = -3.15 ± 0.48, p = 0.00065 ± 0.0016, 193 FDR corrected) similar to previous EEG reports31.
194 In the gamma band we observed a more localized mosaic of ROIs including contralateral motion 195 sensitive areas (inferior lateral occipital region), bilateral extrastriate areas and bilateral frontal 196 motor regions (comprising premotor areas and supplementary motor area; mean across significant 197 ROIs: sign-test z = -2.27 ± 0.27, p = 0.0058 ± 0.003, FDR corrected).
198 Comparisons between z-transformed correlation values from each of the four levels of our 199 manipulations in isolation confirmed that the quality of fit and results did not vary across trials 200 types (p>0.05, FDR corrected).
201 A continuous flow of information 202 We traced the spectrally resolved temporal evolution of decisions through the visuo-motor 203 hierarchy, finding that decision-evidence accumulation emerges with distinct spatio-temporal 204 profiles between beta and gamma (Fig. 4b). An early wave of accumulation begins at ~120ms from 205 coherence onset within the sparse network oscillating at gamma frequency. It is followed by a 206 second wave mediated by Beta at ~160ms from coherence onset (Fig. 4c; Conjunction of significant 207 ROIs in beta and gamma, median latency across participants, z = 5.53, p<0.0001, Wilkoxon rank 208 test). No difference in latencies was found between hemispheres across frequency bands.
