226 primary motor cortex and part of the premotor cortex) as the point of convergence of two linear 227 functions (R2 = 0.734, p < 0.0001) and outperformed a single regression model (piecewise R2 adj = 228 0.681; linear R2 adj = 0.649; adjusted R2 penalizes extra free parameters in favor of simple models).
229 230 Figure 5. A quasi-parallel cascade of decision-evidence accumulation unfolds along the caudo-rostral 231 axis of the dorsal path (a) Regions of interest (ROIs) along the dorsal path color-coded with respect to their 232 position along the caudo-rostral axis (b) Decision-evidence accumulation mediated by beta follows a caudo233 rostral gradient along the dorsal path of the contralateral hemisphere. A piecewise regression (top left panel) 234 best describes the gradient showing that latencies increase from visual areas up to M1 in the precentral gyrus 235 and decrease afterwards suggesting two separate converging flows (Error bars indicate SEM, shaded area 236 covers bootstrapped 95% regression CI). The pattern is inverted for gamma where latencies increase while 237 proceeding from M1 to posterior and anterior ROIs. Despite the differences in latencies along the gradient, 238 the cascade of decision-evidence accumulation is quasi-parallel. The right panels show that the latest ROI in 239 the gradient starts accumulating decision-evidence before the earliest ROI (e.g. V1 for beta) has reached the 240 decision boundary. RT hat is the mean reaction time (across trials and participants) normalized by the mean 241 non-decision time (t0). 242 Interestingly, in the gamma band (Fig. 5b bottom left panel) we found a mirror-symmetric trend 243 with increasing accumulation latencies while proceeding from the precentral gyrus to more 244 posterior and anterior regions (R2 = 0.245, p = 0.042). Thus, accumulation starts with gamma at 245 ~120ms from coherence onset in the precentral gyrus and at ~160ms in the occipital and frontal 246 poles.
12

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
247 The onset of the accumulation in beta overlaps with gamma in the occipital pole at ~160ms from 248 coherence onset34. The interval from earliest onset of accumulation to last onset, is only ~100ms 249 and the onset in precentral gyrus is on average ~570ms before a motor response35. The delay from 250 motion onset to the beginning of the accumulation on the occipital pole (~160ms), and the delay 251 from action decision to movement initiation in precentral gyrus (~100ms) are close to the sensory 252 (~200ms) and motor (~80ms) delays measured from neural recordings on macaque11,36. 253 These patterns, albeit with lower spatial resolution, were also found at the sensor level (SI 254 Appendix, Fig. S4). As a note of caution for the piecewise regression, the fit of the LBA model 255 for some of the ROIs within the dorsal path was not significant in the gamma band, reducing the 256 accuracy of their latency estimates. 257 An important observation is that the latest ROIs in the gradient for both beta and gamma starts 258 accumulating decision-evidence before the earliest ROI (e.g. the occipital lobe for beta) has reached 259 its decision boundary (Fig. 5b right top-bottom panels). This suggests that decisions are made on 260 the basis of a continuous flow of information, rather than a serial sequence of discrete decisions.
