291 Fig. 6b show the smooth global pattern of preferential information flow in the beta range with 292 caudal ROIs preferentially sending information to anterior regions. This pattern is similar to that 293 reported previous work in human resting state22, except that our results show a task-related 294 lateralization, with the contralateral PAx almost twice the size of the ipsilateral one (left: p = 295 0.0001, PAx = 0.357; right: p = 0.0083; PAx = 0.184; left vs right PAx, p<0.0001).
296 297 Figure 6. Sensitivity to uncertainty and information flow, show distinct spatiotemporal gradients. (a) 298 Differences in phase transfer entropy between manipulations of perceptual and action uncertainty for beta 299 (left column) and gamma (right column) allows to define regions accumulating information specific to 300 perception and action decision. (b) Information flow (directional phase transfer entropy) shows a clear rostro301 caudal gradient in beta with MT-complex and the frontal regions being the strongest sender and receiver of 302 information, respectively. (c) Thresholded connectivity plots. Beta activity reflects transmission of 303 information across distant cortical regions mostly within the left hemisphere. Gamma shows a more local 304 activity with no clear lateralization. The full names of the ROIs are given in Table S2.
