bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
350 Discussion 351 352 There are two principal results from this study that illuminate the interaction between neural systems 353 for perception and action. First, decisions in regions sensitive to motor precision do not wait until 354 regional sensory decisions are completed. Instead, the accumulation of evidence in motor decisions 355 begins within 100ms after the initiation of evidence accumulation in the early sensory regions. This 356 indicates a continuous flow or cascade of information and its gradual transformation from sensory 357 evidence to motor intention45. Second, the correlates of evidence-accumulation in the beta and gamma 358 frequency ranges have distinct spatiotemporal profiles, and opposite dominant directions of flow. This 359 spectral directionality is predicted by hierarchical cortical networks for prediction and inference in 360 visuomotor control18,46–48. In the beta band, there is not only a spatial gradient in the timing of 361 accumulation-to-threshold between occipital and pre-central cortex, but also a qualitative change in the 362 accumulated signals: from sensitivity to visual uncertainty to sensitivity to response uncertainty. 363 Variability in the strength of the beta-mediated flow of information connecting visual to motor areas, 364 accounts for participants’ decision speed and corresponds to variability in the evidence accumulation 365 rate (Fig. 7b). This relationship points to the strength of information flow as a neurophysiological 366 correlate of the speed of evidence accumulation towards a decision. 367 368 We set out to integrate the analysis of information flow with decision-making implemented by the 369 accumulation of evidence, and assess their joint influence on trial-to-trial variation in behavior (see Fig. 370 1). Independent manipulation of perceptual and action uncertainty was coupled with the decomposition 371 of performance into latent variables in a parsimonious linear ballistic accumulator model23, which 372 accurately generated the response distributions in each task condition including the expected effects of 373 task variance on response latencies11,14. The model predictions of within-trial accumulation were 374 correlated with change in beta and gamma power after the onset of stimulus coherence. Beta 375 desynchronization has been shown to scale with uncertainty30, but here we show its interaction with the 376 temporal evolution of decision making over sub-second intervals. The observed desynchronization 377 displays two signatures of the accumulation-to-threshold class of models: accumulation of decision378 evidence over time and the consistent bound reached shortly before each movement10,29,35. 379 380 Beta and gamma desynchronization are correlated with behavioural performance. For example, in direct 381 recording from non-human primates during working memory49 and sensory discrimination50, the beta 382 band desynchronization was greater for accurate trials compared with inaccurate trials. Such beta power 383 encoding of decision outcomes is supramodal in many cortical areas20. The change in beta power 384 followed the change in gamma power as in the current study: we found an early wave of gamma 385 followed by a second wave of beta.
18

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
386 387 Although gamma and beta rhythms have been observed to occur together or in close succession51,52, the 388 temporal relationship is functionally relevant. For hierarchical cortical networks, message passing 389 between regions is a function of the laminar asymmetry of afferent vs. efferent connections46, and the 390 properties of columnar circuitry which preferentially generates gamma rhythms superficially, and lower 391 frequencies from deep layers53,54. This promotes predictive feedback connectivity in beta and lower 392 frequencies, and preferential feedforward ‘error’ signalling in gamma18,48. The beta band’s lower 393 frequency makes it inherently more suitable for coordination of information processing over longer 394 conduction delays33. As seen in Fig. 4, where changes in spectral power were predicted by the LBA 395 model, the latency to accumulation was confirmed as shorter for gamma than beta. Indeed, the spatial 396 distribution of beta latencies in the dominant hemisphere (Fig. 5b) shows a gradient from occipital, to 397 parietal and prefrontal, and lastly motor cortex. The motor cortex is also a region of strong net influx 398 of beta (Fig. 6b), even more than premotor cortex, consistent with the active inference model of motor 399 control18,48. 400 401 The spatial gradient of gamma latencies is reversed, with earliest changes observed in precentral cortex, 402 before occipital cortex, and later gamma latencies in time with beta responses in occipital cortex. This 403 may be because of the difference between predicting when a response may be required and what that 404 response should be55. The sensory stimulus change (visual coherence) in our task is not the result of the 405 participant’s own response, but is predictable a second after the onset of the non-coherent display. The 406 participant can predict when an action is required, but not which actions are permitted or specified. An 407 increase in localized and predominantly short-range interactions in gamma range may therefore be a 408 permissive of information required for the beta-mediated decision between action alternatives56. 409 410 Despite the similar latency of beta and gamma accumulators in occipital cortex, the connectivity 411 analyses indicate distinct routing information at longer and shorter spatial scales, respectively. The 412 pattern of net efflux vs. influx of beta (Fig. 6b) shows a clear division between frontal cortex and 413 posterior lobes. Moreover, the more sensitive a region is to action uncertainty (vs. perceptual 414 uncertainty), the later its onset of beta accumulation, and the greater its bias to inflow (vs. outflow, Fig. 415 7a). In other words, there was a cascade of overlapping accumulators and information flow along a 416 rostro-caudal axis from perceptual to motor regions for beta, at least in the hemisphere contralateral to 417 the response hand. 418 419 Lateralized beta activity during a decision-making task reflects not just movement preparation, but has 420 also been related to a dynamic decision process with updating of a motor plan as a decision 421 evolves29,30,35. The beta power lateralization in motor areas was correlated with the state of decision-
19

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
422 evidence. Crucially, these earlier MEG and EEG studies used a fixed-mapping between decisions 423 outcomes and categorical behavioural responses, without choice or independence of perception and 424 action decisions. When this fixed mapping between perceptual decisions outcome and motor responses 425 is removed, sensorimotor beta lateralization disappears57. Our findings complement this work by 426 directly revealing a lateralized progression of evidence accumulation from posterior perceptual regions 427 to anterior motor areas. 428 429 Previous work on visuomotor decisions has often focused on processes occurring at the final choice 430 stage, leaving unresolved the question of whether evidence accumulation is coordinated throughout the 431 cortex or in specific regions. Our findings support a generalized model in which accumulation-to432 threshold provides a canonical mechanism evolving throughout all layers of a visuomotor 433 transformation (Fig. 3a) and suggest that evidence accumulation is not a limited (perceptual) process 434 with a single cortical focus, but is distributed58,59 and applicable to non-sensory evidence or intentions. 435 This multi-focal property of evidence accumulation resonates with results from animal optogenetic58 436 and pharmacological59 studies showing that inactivation of local cortical areas carrying decision-related 437 activity did not affect decision-making performance. 438 439 Taken together, our observations suggest that the beta band response links sensory evidence to motor 440 plans, throughout a widespread network60. We propose that an early neural signalling regarding the 441 need for a response is followed by a second phase that integrates a continuous flow of information to 442 make a decision between them61. In this second phase, decisions unfold on the basis of a continuous 443 flow of information (Fig. 5b), rather than sequential completion of intermediate decisions at the 444 population level. However, this hypothesis refers to the population level, and we cannot exclude the 445 possibility that within each region, a subsection of neurons completes the relevant decision and forwards 446 this outcome to the next level in the hierarchy, while others in that region continue to accumulate. 447 448 The fluctuations in the strength of information flow caused by changes in uncertainty are behaviourally 449 relevant, in their positive correlation with accumulation-rate and negative correlation with reaction 450 times. This establishes an important formal link between behaviour, models of decision-making, and 451 physiological connectivity: Fast accumulating-rates of the linear ballistic accumulator model are 452 associated with a more effective beta-mediated information flow throughout the visuo-motor processing 453 hierarchy, resulting in faster decisions and responses (Fig.7). This link provides a powerful tool to 454 investigate clinical conditions in which the ability to use sensory inputs to guide actions is impaired. 455 Examples include Progressive Supranuclear Palsy, Parkinson’s disease and functional movement 456 disorders, which are associated with abnormal evidence accumulation rates62,63, and abnormal beta 457 power64,65.
20

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
458 459 In summary, our analytical approach set out in Fig 1 elucidates behavioural decisions through the 460 combination of computational modelling of behaviour and identification of neurophysiological 461 signatures of latent variables, in distributed cortical networks. Beta power reflects the temporal and 462 spatial dynamics of the accumulation and transfer of decision-evidence, with a continuous flow of 463 information between regions rather than sequential discrete decisions. During this flow, the gradual 464 transition from the resolution of sensory uncertainty to the resolution of response uncertainty, enables 465 goal-directed actions in the face of uncertainty.
21

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
466 Materials and Methods
467 Participants 468 Twenty healthy volunteers (9 females, 11 males, age range 18-39 years) took part in this study, after 469 providing informed consent. Inclusion criteria included age 18-40 years, right-handed, and screening 470 for neurological or psychiatric illness. Two subjects failed to reach the requisite performance criterion 471 during training and were excluded, leaving 18 subjects in all subsequent behavioral and neural analyses. 472 The chosen sample size was based on previous EEG/MEG studies on perceptual and motor decision473 making35,66. Experimental protocols conformed to the guidelines of the Declarations of Helsinki and 474 were approved by the local research ethics committee.
475 Task and procedures 476 Participants performed a finger-tapping task adapted from previous studies 13,14. Their goal was to 477 detect the onset of coherent motion and to press the button corresponding to one of the downward 478 moving stimuli (coherent stimuli). The number of coherent stimuli defined two trial types: Low action 479 uncertainty trials, where a single coherent stimulus commanded which button to press; and high action 480 uncertainty trials, where three coherent stimuli required the participants to make a simple choice and 481 press any one of the three corresponding buttons (a “fresh choice, regardless of what you have done in 482 previous trials”14). Equal emphasis was placed on the speed and accuracy of the responses. Participants 483 were instructed to fixate on a central red mark throughout the trial. Eye-tracking data collected during 484 the first six scanning sessions confirmed participants were able to successfully perform the task while 485 maintaining fixation (see SI Appendix, Fig. S5). Each trial started with the presentation of the fixation 486 mark and stimuli onset ensued after a variable interval comprised between 0.5sec and 1sec. The imaging 487 session was preceded by one training psychophysical session and one test session scheduled on separate 488 days; the scanning session was conducted a maximum of four days after the psychophysical training, 489 depending on the availability of the participants. The test session was to ensure that the participants 490 were able to perform well under the individually adjusted motion thresholds. In the test and scan 491 sessions, coherence levels were fixed to the individual thresholds corresponding to high and low levels 492 of perceptual uncertainty, the match-to-sample task was removed, and no feedback was provided except 493 for too late or too long responses. Levels of perceptual and action uncertainty where randomly 494 interspersed across trials. Each session consisted of 10 blocks (total 720 trials per participant) separated 495 by a short rest. Trials on which responses were made before 0.1-sec or after 2-sec (on average 1.3% of 496 total trials) were excluded from subsequent analyses.
22

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
497 Stimuli 498 Stimuli were presented using Matlab (Matworks, Natiek, MA, USA) and the Psychotoolbox routines in 499 a sound-proof and dimly lit room. For the psychophysical training stimuli were displayed on a CRT 500 monitor at 60cm, and for the scan session stimuli were projected on a screen through a projector at 501 130cm (both with a 60Hz refresh rate) with equivalent pixel resolution of 0.03°.
502 Stimuli were four random dot kinematograms displayed within four circular apertures (4° diameter) 503 positioned along a notional semi-circular arc (3.4° eccentricity) on a black background (100% contrast). 504 200 dots were displayed during each frame and spatially displaced in the next frame to introduce 505 apparent downward motion (6°/sec velocity). To manipulate motion strength (i.e. motion coherence) 506 between trials, on each frame only a certain proportion of dots moved downward whilst the rest of the 507 dots where randomly reallocated. Motion coherence level was kept constant throughout the trial.
508 Since abrupt stimulus onset and offset could elicit large sensory-evoked potentials which might mask 509 decision processes, the 1.5 seconds long coherent motion interval was preceded and followed by 510 intervals of zero-coherence levels lasting 1sec and 0.5sec, respectively.
511 Psychometric calibration 512 Participants were firstly familiarized with the finger-tapping task during a short practice session where 513 100% coherent stimuli were adopted. The familiarization phase was completed when participants 514 reached 90% accuracy across all trial types. In the following psychophysical training, motion 515 coherence was randomly varied between trials to estimate individual motion thresholds. Eight 516 logarithmically spaced motion coherence levels (0 0.5 0.10….0.9) were used (32 trials per level) 517 following extensive piloting to ensure coverage of a wide range of individual motion sensitivity. Each 518 training session comprised 16 blocks of 32 trials. Feedback was provided for correctness of responses 519 as well as for too early or too late responses (100ms and 2.5s from motion coherence onset, 520 respectively).
521 To ensure that participants perceived all the available options (i.e. coherent stimuli) before committing 522 to a decision, occasionally (p = 0.2) after a correct choice they had to perform a secondary match-to523 sample task: a set of grey discs replaced the stimuli and participants had to report whether their locations 524 matched the location of the previously displayed coherent stimuli. They had to press any button to report 525 a match and withhold any response otherwise. A trial was considered as correct only when both choice 526 and matching were correct. Trials with un-matching responses were discarded and repeated within the 527 session.
23

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.

528 To tailor the sensory evidence to the participants’ individual motion sensitivity across number of 529 options, the discrimination accuracy of each trial type in each training session was fitted using a 530 maximum likelihood method, with a Log-Quick function defined as

531 !"# = 1 − 2$%&!(#$%) ,

(1)

532 where α is the threshold, β is the slope and x is the coherence level. To obtain the proportion correct for 533 each trial type, the Log-Quick function was scaled by,

534  =  + (1 −  − )!"# ,

(2)

535 where γ is the guess rate and λ is the lapse rate controlling the lower and upper asymptote of the 536 psychometric function, respectively.

537 Individual low and high perceptual uncertainty levels for each trial type were estimated as the 75th and 538 90th percentile of the psychometric functions from the last session. The reason for adopting these 539 thresholds was twofold: firstly, participants need to perceive all the available options before committing 540 to a decision. Secondly, supra-threshold trials are best suited for investigating neural correlates of 541 evidence accumulation 67.

542 MEG and EEG data acquisition and processing
543 An Elekta Neuromag Vectorview System (Helsinki, Finland) simultaneously acquired magnetic fields 544 from 102 magnetometers and 204 paired planar gradiometers, and electrical potential from 70 EEG 545 electrodes (70 Ag-AgCl scalp electrodes in an Easycap - GmbH, Herrsching, Germany - extended 10546 10% system). Additional electrodes provided a nasal reference, a forehead ground, paired horizontal 547 and vertical electro-oculography, electrocardiography and neck electromyography. All data were 548 recorded and digitized continuously at a sample rate of 1kHz and high-pass filtered above 0.01 Hz.
549 Before scanning, head shape, the locations of five evenly distributed head position indicator coils, EEG 550 electrodes location, and the position of three anatomical fiducial points (nasion and left and right pre551 auricular) were recorded using a 3D digitizer (Fastrak Polhemus Inc., Colchester, VA). The initial 552 impedence of all EEG electrodes was optimized to below 10 kΩ, and if this could not be achieved in a 553 particular channel, or if it appeared noisy to visual inspection, it was excluded from further analysis. 554 The 3D position of the head position indicators relative to the MEG sensors was monitored throughout 555 the scan.

24

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.
556 Environmental noise suppression, motion compensation, and Signal Source Separation for the MEG 557 data was followed by separate independent component analysis for the three sensor types and artifactual 558 components were rejected. For EEG data, components temporally and spatially correlated to eye 559 movements, blinks and cardiac activity were automatically identified with EEGLab’s toolbox ADJUST 560 (Swartz Center for Computational Neuroscience, University of California San Diego). For MEG data, 561 components were automatically identified that were both significantly temporally correlated with 562 electrooculography and electrocardiography data, and spatially correlated with separately acquired 563 topographies for ocular and cardiac artifacts using in-house Matlab code.
564 The continuous artefact-corrected data were low-pass filtered (cut-off = 100Hz, Butterworth, fourth 565 order), notch filtered between 48 and 52Hz to remove main power supply artifacts, down-sampled to 566 250Hz, and epoched from -1500 to 2500ms relative to motion coherence onset. EEG data were 567 referenced to the average over electrodes.
568 MEG and EEG data were combined before inversion into source space 21 using the Miminum Norm 569 algorithm as implemented by SPM12. Notably, combined MEG and EEG allows a better localization 570 of neural sources than each technique on its own21. The forward model was estimated from each 571 participant’s anatomical T1-weighted MRI image. All conditions were included in the inversion to 572 ensure an unbiased linear mapping. The source images were spatially smoothed using an 8 mm FWHM 573 Gaussian kernel.
574 Accumulator model of perceptual and action decisions 575 We adopted formal models of decision-making to decompose the behavioral performance into 576 cognitively relevant latent variables. We fitted accumulation-to-threshold models (Linear Ballistic 577 Accumulator23, LBA), to each participant’s reaction time and accuracy data. The LBA model of 578 decisions is more tractable than drift-diffusion models for n-way decisions while still remaining 579 physiologically informative68 and has been previously applied to a finger tapping task to model fMRI 580 evidence accumulation13. Instead of adopting a two-stage model, which assumes a discrete serial 581 process between perceptual and action decisions, we opted for a ‘unitary’ model where both perceptual 582 and action uncertainty concur in determining participant’s performance in a given trial. The factorial 583 design of the experiment enabled us to divorce perceptual and action decision processes using 584 connectivity metrics.
585 According to this class of models, each accumulator linearly integrates the decision-evidence (or the 586 intention) over time in favor of one action, and the decision is made when the accumulated activity 587 reaches threshold (see Fig.3c). In our task possible actions correspond to a button press from one of
25

bioRxiv preprint doi: https://doi.org/10.1101/803049. this version posted May 15, 2020. The copyright holder for this preprint (which was not certified by peer review) is the author/funder. It is made available under a CC-BY-NC-ND 4.0 International license.

588 four fingers, each modeled by independent accumulators i Î{1, 2, 3, 4}. When three valid actions are 589 available, three accumulators are engaged with activation starting at levels independently drawn from 590 a uniform distribution [0, c0], and increasing linearly over time with an accumulation rate (v) drawn 591 from an independent normal distribution with mean µi and standard deviation si. A response is triggered 592 once one accumulator wins the ‘race’ and reaches a decision bound (b). When only one action is 593 available, only the accumulator corresponding to the available action is engaged. Predicted reaction 594 time (RT) is given by the duration of the accumulation process for the winning accumulator, plus a 595 constant non-decision time t0 representing the latency associated with stimulus encoding and motor 596 response initiation23.
597 To identify the combinations of free parameters that best accounted for the observed behavioral data 598 we firstly fitted 15 variants (i.e. all possible combinations without repetition) of the LBA. Each variant 599 was characterized by a unique combination of free parameters allowed to vary across trials. The best600 fitting parameters for each model variant were used to calculate the Bayesian Information Criterion 601 (BIC), which penalizes extra free parameters in favor of simpler models. BIC values were then used to 602 compare the goodness-of-fit of each variant using random-effects Bayesian model comparison 24,25. 603 Predictions of decision-related activity were generated from the winning LBA model to locate neural 604 signatures of decisions-evidence accumulation in single-trial analyses of MEEG data.

605 Estimation of expected neural activity
